</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Breast density, fibroglandular tissue, and background parenchymal enhancement (BPE) are recognized independent biomarkers for breast cancer risk. For this reason, reproducibility and consistency in objective assessment of these parameters at mammography (breast density) and at magnetic resonance imaging (fibroglandular tissue and BPE) are clinically relevant. However, breast density, fibroglandular tissue, and BPE are manifestations of dynamic physiologic processes and may change in response to both endogenous and exogenous hormonal stimulation. It is therefore important for the radiologist to recognize settings in which hormonal stimulation may alter the appearance of these biomarkers at imaging and to appreciate how such changes may affect risk assessment, cancer detection, and even prognosis. The purpose of this review article is therefore to review key features and means of evaluating breast density, fibroglandular tissue, and BPE at imaging; to detail how endogenous and exogenous hormonal stimuli may affect breast density, fibroglandular tissue, and BPE, potentially affecting radiologic interpretation; and, finally, to provide an update regarding current hormone treatment guidelines and indications that may result in imaging changes through hormone modulation.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018180035">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018180035">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig1a.jpeg" height="1798" width="1067" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Decreased breast density with aging. <b>(a)</b> Right mediolateral oblique (MLO) mammographic view of a 30-year-old premenopausal woman shows extremely dense breasts (BI-RADS category d). <b>(b)</b> Right MLO view of the same woman obtained when she was 55 years old and postmenopausal shows that involution of the breast tissue has occurred, resulting in heterogeneously dense breasts (BI-RADS category c).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig1b.jpeg" height="1798" width="1005" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Decreased breast density with aging. <b>(a)</b> Right mediolateral oblique (MLO) mammographic view of a 30-year-old premenopausal woman shows extremely dense breasts (BI-RADS category d). <b>(b)</b> Right MLO view of the same woman obtained when she was 55 years old and postmenopausal shows that involution of the breast tissue has occurred, resulting in heterogeneously dense breasts (BI-RADS category c).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig2a.jpeg" height="1792" width="865" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Increased breast density owing to lactation in a 42-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Right MLO <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> mammographic views show breast density before lactation. Breast parenchyma is classified as scattered fibroglandular (BI-RADS category b). <b>(c, d)</b> Right MLO <b>(c)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(d)</b> mammographic views obtained during lactation show an increase in breast density owing to lactational changes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig2b.jpeg" height="1796" width="783" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Increased breast density owing to lactation in a 42-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Right MLO <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> mammographic views show breast density before lactation. Breast parenchyma is classified as scattered fibroglandular (BI-RADS category b). <b>(c, d)</b> Right MLO <b>(c)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(d)</b> mammographic views obtained during lactation show an increase in breast density owing to lactational changes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig2c.jpeg" height="1796" width="1030" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Increased breast density owing to lactation in a 42-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Right MLO <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> mammographic views show breast density before lactation. Breast parenchyma is classified as scattered fibroglandular (BI-RADS category b). <b>(c, d)</b> Right MLO <b>(c)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(d)</b> mammographic views obtained during lactation show an increase in breast density owing to lactational changes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig2d.jpeg" height="1796" width="947" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span>. Increased breast density owing to lactation in a 42-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Right MLO <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> mammographic views show breast density before lactation. Breast parenchyma is classified as scattered fibroglandular (BI-RADS category b). <b>(c, d)</b> Right MLO <b>(c)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(d)</b> mammographic views obtained during lactation show an increase in breast density owing to lactational changes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig3a.jpeg" height="2179" width="912" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Increase in breast density owing to hormone replacement therapy. <b>(a)</b> Screening mammogram of a 53-year-old woman shows breast density at baseline. <b>(b–d)</b> Mammograms of the same patient obtained over the following 3 years after beginning hormone replacement therapy show increased breast density. Ultrasonography helped confirm the development of multiple cysts after the start of hormone replacement therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig3b.jpeg" height="2179" width="953" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Increase in breast density owing to hormone replacement therapy. <b>(a)</b> Screening mammogram of a 53-year-old woman shows breast density at baseline. <b>(b–d)</b> Mammograms of the same patient obtained over the following 3 years after beginning hormone replacement therapy show increased breast density. Ultrasonography helped confirm the development of multiple cysts after the start of hormone replacement therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig3c.jpeg" height="2179" width="949" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Increase in breast density owing to hormone replacement therapy. <b>(a)</b> Screening mammogram of a 53-year-old woman shows breast density at baseline. <b>(b–d)</b> Mammograms of the same patient obtained over the following 3 years after beginning hormone replacement therapy show increased breast density. Ultrasonography helped confirm the development of multiple cysts after the start of hormone replacement therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig3d.jpeg" height="2179" width="845" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Increase in breast density owing to hormone replacement therapy. <b>(a)</b> Screening mammogram of a 53-year-old woman shows breast density at baseline. <b>(b–d)</b> Mammograms of the same patient obtained over the following 3 years after beginning hormone replacement therapy show increased breast density. Ultrasonography helped confirm the development of multiple cysts after the start of hormone replacement therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig4a.jpeg" height="2598" width="946" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Increased breast density in a transgender individual after hormonal treatment. <b>(a)</b> Right MLO mammographic view of a 20-year-old male-to-female transgender patient shows the breast density at baseline. <b>(b)</b> Right MLO mammographic view of the same patient obtained 2 years later shows a diffuse increase in breast density after hormonal treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig4b.jpeg" height="2598" width="816" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Increased breast density in a transgender individual after hormonal treatment. <b>(a)</b> Right MLO mammographic view of a 20-year-old male-to-female transgender patient shows the breast density at baseline. <b>(b)</b> Right MLO mammographic view of the same patient obtained 2 years later shows a diffuse increase in breast density after hormonal treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig5a.jpeg" height="743" width="1934" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Lack of correlation of BPE with the amount of fibroglandular tissue in a 45-year-old woman with a strong family history of breast cancer who presented for screening mammography. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted non–fat-suppressed MR image (3.27/1.45 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]; flip angle, 12°; field of view [FOV], 352 mm; section thickness, 1.10 mm) shows extreme fibroglandular tissue. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed subtraction MR image (3.27/1.45; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 352 mm; section thickness, 1.10 mm) shows minimal to mild BPE.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig5b.jpeg" height="747" width="1821" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Lack of correlation of BPE with the amount of fibroglandular tissue in a 45-year-old woman with a strong family history of breast cancer who presented for screening mammography. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced T1-weighted non–fat-suppressed MR image (3.27/1.45 [repetition time msec/echo time msec]; flip angle, 12°; field of view [FOV], 352 mm; section thickness, 1.10 mm) shows extreme fibroglandular tissue. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed subtraction MR image (3.27/1.45; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 352 mm; section thickness, 1.10 mm) shows minimal to mild BPE.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig6a.jpeg" height="1822" width="1013" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Influence of the menstrual cycle on BPE. Sagittal contrast-enhanced subtraction MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm) of a 41-year-old premenopausal woman show that the amount of BPE is relatively decreased on the image obtained during the 2nd week of her menstrual cycle <b>(a)</b>, compared with the increased BPE on the image obtained during the 4th week of her cycle <b>(b)</b> .<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig6b.jpeg" height="1822" width="1029" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Influence of the menstrual cycle on BPE. Sagittal contrast-enhanced subtraction MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm) of a 41-year-old premenopausal woman show that the amount of BPE is relatively decreased on the image obtained during the 2nd week of her menstrual cycle <b>(a)</b>, compared with the increased BPE on the image obtained during the 4th week of her cycle <b>(b)</b> .<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig7a.jpeg" height="1230" width="1968" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Increased BPE associated with lactation: axial contrast-enhanced subtraction MR images (3.27/1.45; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 352 mm; section thickness, 1.10 mm) of a 36-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Image obtained during lactation shows marked BPE secondary to increased vascularity and proliferative change. <b>(b)</b> Repeat image obtained 6 months after the discontinuation of breast-feeding shows decreased amount of BPE.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig7b.jpeg" height="1230" width="1782" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Increased BPE associated with lactation: axial contrast-enhanced subtraction MR images (3.27/1.45; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 352 mm; section thickness, 1.10 mm) of a 36-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Image obtained during lactation shows marked BPE secondary to increased vascularity and proliferative change. <b>(b)</b> Repeat image obtained 6 months after the discontinuation of breast-feeding shows decreased amount of BPE.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig8a.jpeg" height="2226" width="975" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Therapy with SERMs, such as tamoxifen, reduces breast density and fibroglandular tissue to a greater extent in women with dense breasts, as shown in two different patients. The higher the baseline breast density, the greater the percentage reduction after treatment. <b>(a, b)</b> Right MLO mammographic views of a 60-year-old woman who had undergone left mastectomy for invasive ductal carcinoma: <b>(a)</b> Image shows breast density at the beginning of adjuvant tamoxifen therapy. <b>(b)</b> Image of the same patient obtained 4 years later shows an interval decrease in breast density compared with <b>a</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Left MLO mammographic views of a 56-year-old woman: <b>(c)</b> Baseline image obtained before the start of tamoxifen therapy shows scattered fibroglandular tissue. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up image obtained after treatment (for a similar length of time as that of the 60-year-old patient) shows no difference in breast density compared with <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig8b.jpeg" height="2226" width="969" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Therapy with SERMs, such as tamoxifen, reduces breast density and fibroglandular tissue to a greater extent in women with dense breasts, as shown in two different patients. The higher the baseline breast density, the greater the percentage reduction after treatment. <b>(a, b)</b> Right MLO mammographic views of a 60-year-old woman who had undergone left mastectomy for invasive ductal carcinoma: <b>(a)</b> Image shows breast density at the beginning of adjuvant tamoxifen therapy. <b>(b)</b> Image of the same patient obtained 4 years later shows an interval decrease in breast density compared with <b>a</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Left MLO mammographic views of a 56-year-old woman: <b>(c)</b> Baseline image obtained before the start of tamoxifen therapy shows scattered fibroglandular tissue. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up image obtained after treatment (for a similar length of time as that of the 60-year-old patient) shows no difference in breast density compared with <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig8c.jpeg" height="2226" width="854" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Therapy with SERMs, such as tamoxifen, reduces breast density and fibroglandular tissue to a greater extent in women with dense breasts, as shown in two different patients. The higher the baseline breast density, the greater the percentage reduction after treatment. <b>(a, b)</b> Right MLO mammographic views of a 60-year-old woman who had undergone left mastectomy for invasive ductal carcinoma: <b>(a)</b> Image shows breast density at the beginning of adjuvant tamoxifen therapy. <b>(b)</b> Image of the same patient obtained 4 years later shows an interval decrease in breast density compared with <b>a</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Left MLO mammographic views of a 56-year-old woman: <b>(c)</b> Baseline image obtained before the start of tamoxifen therapy shows scattered fibroglandular tissue. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up image obtained after treatment (for a similar length of time as that of the 60-year-old patient) shows no difference in breast density compared with <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig8d.jpeg" height="2226" width="866" aria-labelledby="fig8d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8d</span>. Therapy with SERMs, such as tamoxifen, reduces breast density and fibroglandular tissue to a greater extent in women with dense breasts, as shown in two different patients. The higher the baseline breast density, the greater the percentage reduction after treatment. <b>(a, b)</b> Right MLO mammographic views of a 60-year-old woman who had undergone left mastectomy for invasive ductal carcinoma: <b>(a)</b> Image shows breast density at the beginning of adjuvant tamoxifen therapy. <b>(b)</b> Image of the same patient obtained 4 years later shows an interval decrease in breast density compared with <b>a</b>. <b>(c, d)</b> Left MLO mammographic views of a 56-year-old woman: <b>(c)</b> Baseline image obtained before the start of tamoxifen therapy shows scattered fibroglandular tissue. <b>(d)</b> Follow-up image obtained after treatment (for a similar length of time as that of the 60-year-old patient) shows no difference in breast density compared with <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig8d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig9a.jpeg" height="1769" width="883" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Reduction of fibroglandular tissue after tamoxifen therapy in a 39-year-old woman with a history of a benign left breast excision in whom an invasive ductal carcinoma of the left breast was diagnosed. The patient underwent lumpectomy, chemotherapy, and tamoxifen treatment. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted non–fat-suppressed MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(a)</b> Initial image obtained at the time of diagnosis shows heterogeneously dense fibroglandular tissue. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up image obtained 1 year later shows a reduction in fibroglandular tissue. However, changes in mammographic breast density were qualitatively more difficult to appreciate. <b>(c, d)</b> MLO mammographic views from the same two time points: <b>(c)</b> Baseline mammogram at diagnosis shows the left breast cancer (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Follow-up mammogram was obtained 1 year later. These findings are suggestive that fibroglandular tissue volume at MR imaging may serve as a more sensitive biomarker than mammographic breast density in this setting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig9b.jpeg" height="1769" width="954" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Reduction of fibroglandular tissue after tamoxifen therapy in a 39-year-old woman with a history of a benign left breast excision in whom an invasive ductal carcinoma of the left breast was diagnosed. The patient underwent lumpectomy, chemotherapy, and tamoxifen treatment. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted non–fat-suppressed MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(a)</b> Initial image obtained at the time of diagnosis shows heterogeneously dense fibroglandular tissue. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up image obtained 1 year later shows a reduction in fibroglandular tissue. However, changes in mammographic breast density were qualitatively more difficult to appreciate. <b>(c, d)</b> MLO mammographic views from the same two time points: <b>(c)</b> Baseline mammogram at diagnosis shows the left breast cancer (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Follow-up mammogram was obtained 1 year later. These findings are suggestive that fibroglandular tissue volume at MR imaging may serve as a more sensitive biomarker than mammographic breast density in this setting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig9c.jpeg" height="1769" width="904" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Reduction of fibroglandular tissue after tamoxifen therapy in a 39-year-old woman with a history of a benign left breast excision in whom an invasive ductal carcinoma of the left breast was diagnosed. The patient underwent lumpectomy, chemotherapy, and tamoxifen treatment. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted non–fat-suppressed MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(a)</b> Initial image obtained at the time of diagnosis shows heterogeneously dense fibroglandular tissue. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up image obtained 1 year later shows a reduction in fibroglandular tissue. However, changes in mammographic breast density were qualitatively more difficult to appreciate. <b>(c, d)</b> MLO mammographic views from the same two time points: <b>(c)</b> Baseline mammogram at diagnosis shows the left breast cancer (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Follow-up mammogram was obtained 1 year later. These findings are suggestive that fibroglandular tissue volume at MR imaging may serve as a more sensitive biomarker than mammographic breast density in this setting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig9d.jpeg" height="1769" width="894" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Reduction of fibroglandular tissue after tamoxifen therapy in a 39-year-old woman with a history of a benign left breast excision in whom an invasive ductal carcinoma of the left breast was diagnosed. The patient underwent lumpectomy, chemotherapy, and tamoxifen treatment. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal T1-weighted non–fat-suppressed MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(a)</b> Initial image obtained at the time of diagnosis shows heterogeneously dense fibroglandular tissue. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up image obtained 1 year later shows a reduction in fibroglandular tissue. However, changes in mammographic breast density were qualitatively more difficult to appreciate. <b>(c, d)</b> MLO mammographic views from the same two time points: <b>(c)</b> Baseline mammogram at diagnosis shows the left breast cancer (arrow). <b>(d)</b> Follow-up mammogram was obtained 1 year later. These findings are suggestive that fibroglandular tissue volume at MR imaging may serve as a more sensitive biomarker than mammographic breast density in this setting.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig10a.jpeg" height="1374" width="1245" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. More pronounced effect of tamoxifen therapy on BPE than on fibroglandular tissue in a 41-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment image shows baseline BPE. <b>(b)</b> Image obtained after tamoxifen treatment shows complete suppression of BPE. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal nonenhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(c)</b> Pretreatment image shows baseline fibroglandular tissue. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained after tamoxifen treatment shows little change in the amount of fibroglandular tissue, compared with that shown on <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig10b.jpeg" height="1374" width="1220" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. More pronounced effect of tamoxifen therapy on BPE than on fibroglandular tissue in a 41-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment image shows baseline BPE. <b>(b)</b> Image obtained after tamoxifen treatment shows complete suppression of BPE. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal nonenhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(c)</b> Pretreatment image shows baseline fibroglandular tissue. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained after tamoxifen treatment shows little change in the amount of fibroglandular tissue, compared with that shown on <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig10c.jpeg" height="1374" width="1239" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. More pronounced effect of tamoxifen therapy on BPE than on fibroglandular tissue in a 41-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment image shows baseline BPE. <b>(b)</b> Image obtained after tamoxifen treatment shows complete suppression of BPE. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal nonenhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(c)</b> Pretreatment image shows baseline fibroglandular tissue. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained after tamoxifen treatment shows little change in the amount of fibroglandular tissue, compared with that shown on <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig10d.jpeg" height="1418" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span>. More pronounced effect of tamoxifen therapy on BPE than on fibroglandular tissue in a 41-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(a)</b> Pretreatment image shows baseline BPE. <b>(b)</b> Image obtained after tamoxifen treatment shows complete suppression of BPE. <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal nonenhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm): <b>(c)</b> Pretreatment image shows baseline fibroglandular tissue. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained after tamoxifen treatment shows little change in the amount of fibroglandular tissue, compared with that shown on <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig11a.jpeg" height="1379" width="1203" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Differing effects on BPE from SERM therapy and aromatase inhibitor therapy on sagittal MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm) in two different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> SERM therapy leads to nearly complete suppression of BPE, as shown in this 48-year-old woman with a strong family history of breast cancer: <b>(a)</b> Image obtained at baseline shows BPE. <b>(b)</b> Posttreatment image shows complete suppression of BPE after tamoxifen therapy for chemoprevention. <b>(c, d)</b> On the other hand, aromatase inhibitor therapy causes a less pronounced change in BPE, as shown in this 50-year-old woman who had undergone a left lumpectomy and radiation therapy: <b>(c)</b> Image obtained at baseline shows BPE. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained during subsequent aromatase inhibitor therapy shows a less marked change in BPE than that seen on <b>b</b> after tamoxifen therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig11b.jpeg" height="1517" width="1292" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Differing effects on BPE from SERM therapy and aromatase inhibitor therapy on sagittal MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm) in two different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> SERM therapy leads to nearly complete suppression of BPE, as shown in this 48-year-old woman with a strong family history of breast cancer: <b>(a)</b> Image obtained at baseline shows BPE. <b>(b)</b> Posttreatment image shows complete suppression of BPE after tamoxifen therapy for chemoprevention. <b>(c, d)</b> On the other hand, aromatase inhibitor therapy causes a less pronounced change in BPE, as shown in this 50-year-old woman who had undergone a left lumpectomy and radiation therapy: <b>(c)</b> Image obtained at baseline shows BPE. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained during subsequent aromatase inhibitor therapy shows a less marked change in BPE than that seen on <b>b</b> after tamoxifen therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig11c.jpeg" height="1517" width="1284" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Differing effects on BPE from SERM therapy and aromatase inhibitor therapy on sagittal MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm) in two different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> SERM therapy leads to nearly complete suppression of BPE, as shown in this 48-year-old woman with a strong family history of breast cancer: <b>(a)</b> Image obtained at baseline shows BPE. <b>(b)</b> Posttreatment image shows complete suppression of BPE after tamoxifen therapy for chemoprevention. <b>(c, d)</b> On the other hand, aromatase inhibitor therapy causes a less pronounced change in BPE, as shown in this 50-year-old woman who had undergone a left lumpectomy and radiation therapy: <b>(c)</b> Image obtained at baseline shows BPE. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained during subsequent aromatase inhibitor therapy shows a less marked change in BPE than that seen on <b>b</b> after tamoxifen therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig11d.jpeg" height="1517" width="1130" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span>. Differing effects on BPE from SERM therapy and aromatase inhibitor therapy on sagittal MR images (4.01/1.52; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 270 mm; section thickness, 1 mm) in two different patients. <b>(a, b)</b> SERM therapy leads to nearly complete suppression of BPE, as shown in this 48-year-old woman with a strong family history of breast cancer: <b>(a)</b> Image obtained at baseline shows BPE. <b>(b)</b> Posttreatment image shows complete suppression of BPE after tamoxifen therapy for chemoprevention. <b>(c, d)</b> On the other hand, aromatase inhibitor therapy causes a less pronounced change in BPE, as shown in this 50-year-old woman who had undergone a left lumpectomy and radiation therapy: <b>(c)</b> Image obtained at baseline shows BPE. <b>(d)</b> Image obtained during subsequent aromatase inhibitor therapy shows a less marked change in BPE than that seen on <b>b</b> after tamoxifen therapy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig12a.jpeg" height="1134" width="1828" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Rebound BPE on axial contrast-enhanced subtraction MR images (3.27/1.45; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 352 mm; section thickness, 1.10 mm) in a 54-year-old woman with a history of left lobular carcinoma in situ (2009), who was treated with tamoxifen for 5 years. <b>(a)</b> Image shows minimal BPE during tamoxifen therapy. <b>(b)</b> Image obtained immediately after cessation of tamoxifen therapy shows a marked increase in BPE (rebound BPE). <b>(c)</b> Follow-up image obtained 1 year after <b>b</b> shows a return to minimal BPE after resolution of rebound BPE.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig12b.jpeg" height="1134" width="1908" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Rebound BPE on axial contrast-enhanced subtraction MR images (3.27/1.45; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 352 mm; section thickness, 1.10 mm) in a 54-year-old woman with a history of left lobular carcinoma in situ (2009), who was treated with tamoxifen for 5 years. <b>(a)</b> Image shows minimal BPE during tamoxifen therapy. <b>(b)</b> Image obtained immediately after cessation of tamoxifen therapy shows a marked increase in BPE (rebound BPE). <b>(c)</b> Follow-up image obtained 1 year after <b>b</b> shows a return to minimal BPE after resolution of rebound BPE.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180035/asset/images/large/rg.2018180035.fig12c.jpeg" height="1048" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Rebound BPE on axial contrast-enhanced subtraction MR images (3.27/1.45; flip angle, 12°; FOV, 352 mm; section thickness, 1.10 mm) in a 54-year-old woman with a history of left lobular carcinoma in situ (2009), who was treated with tamoxifen for 5 years. <b>(a)</b> Image shows minimal BPE during tamoxifen therapy. <b>(b)</b> Image obtained immediately after cessation of tamoxifen therapy shows a marked increase in BPE (rebound BPE). <b>(c)</b> Follow-up image obtained 1 year after <b>b</b> shows a return to minimal BPE after resolution of rebound BPE.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180035&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Giordano L, Gallo F, Petracci E, Chiorino G, Segnan N; Andromeda working group. The ANDROMEDA prospective cohort study: predictive value of combined criteria to tailor breast cancer screening and new opportunities from circulating markers—study protocol. <em>BMC Cancer</em> 2017;17(1):785. <a href="https://bmccancer.biomedcentral.com/track/pdf/10.1186/s12885-017-3784-5">https://bmccancer.biomedcentral.com/track/pdf/10.1186/s12885-017-3784-5</a>. Published November 22, 2017.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1186/s12885-017-3784-5">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29166878/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Andromeda+working+group.+The+ANDROMEDA+prospective+cohort+study%3A+predictive